Flatfield correction is a standard technique for removing pixel-to-pixel sensitivity differences that result from detector responsivity variations and optical features such as vignetting, filter imperfections, and dust. Flat field images are derived from uniformly illuminated (i.e., “flat”) targets that highlight sensitivity variations within the field of view. Bias and dark current corrected images are multiplied by normalized flatfield maps in an attempt to cancel the effect of these variations and make every pixel respond like a fictitious average pixel. The average pixel is typically defined as the mean response of a central 200×200\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
