For sensor systems that are not diffraction-limited, the RDL underestimates the GRD. A more accurate measure of the GRD is to compute it using the full width half maximum (FWHM) of the measured system PSF. While accurately measuring a systems’ two dimensional PSF requires a complex test setup, measuring the MTF is considerably simpler. The inverse Fourier transform of the MTF is the Line Spread Function (LSF), which represents a one-dimensional transect of the PSF along the direction of the edge used to measure the MTF. The FWHM of the LSF is a common standard used to characterize the resolution of remote sensing and medical imaging systems (Perkins and Lees 2016). In terms of the FWHM of the LSF, the GRD is: 9GRD=FWHMLSF⋅d.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
